15. ne legaretur . . . Pompeio: that A. Gabinius might nat bc appointed legatus to Cn. Pompey. According to a Roman law, the lex Licinia et Aebutia, no one could receive an appointment under a statute proposed by himself. Hence Gabinius could not be legally appointed a legatio under the Gabinian law. For this reason, Pompey, who had been given the right to appoint his legali, had not ventured to appoint Gabinius, but he finally asked the senate to do so. This demand, however, as Cicero tells us, had been vigorously opposed.
